  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nNote upfront: this is a Python async scraping/dedup pipeline (fetchers → filter → SQLite store → notify), not a web app — there's no React/frontend code in the repo, so that section doesn't apply. I found real issues in the other four categories.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-97` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` loops over every fetched job and issues a separate `SELECT` per job, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)          # separate INSERT\n    else:\n        ...                                   # separate UPDATE\n```\n\nWith 114 sources in `sources.yaml` (several with `max_pages` of 30–40 and thousands of roles — Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Google), a single run can push this into the thousands-of-round-trips range. Even against local SQLite, per-call cursor overhead adds up and this blocks the whole dedup step on serial single-row statements.\n\n**Fix** — one bulk read + `executemany` writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\").fetchall())\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(INSERT_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(UPDATE_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                     [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(1) + 3 batch statements. Loading all keys/hashes into a dict is cheap (a few MB even at tens of thousands of rows) and is a one-time cost per run.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`filter_jobs()` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job call**:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"),\n                                      exclude=rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\"), ...)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every job!\n            return False\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):\n            return False\n```\n\nThe keyword lists are identical for every job in the run, so this recompiles the same set of `re.Pattern` objects thousands of times.\n\n**Fix** — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```//and change `match()` to take already-compiled lists.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation / wasted memory — `Job.to_row()` deep-copies `raw` just to discard it — `models.py:71-75`\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # dataclasses.asdict recursively deep-copies every field,\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # including `raw` — then we throw the copy away\n    ...\n```\n\n`raw` holds the full source API payload for every job (set in every `parse_*` function in `fetchers.py`, e.g. `raw=j`) — and it's grepped nowhere else in the codebase; it's never read. `dataclasses.asdict()` recursively rebuilds/deep-copies nested dicts, so every call to `to_row()` (once per new/changed job, called during `diff()`) pays the cost of deep-copying a full JSON job payload only to drop it a line later. Across thousands of jobs per run that's real, avoidable allocation churn (and GC pressure).\n\n**Fix** — either stop storing `raw` at all (it's dead weight — drop the field or replace with the couple of ID fields fetchers actually want to keep, as `parse_google`/`parse_meta`/`parse_amazon` already do selectively), or avoid `asdict` for the hot path:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company, \"external_id\": self.external_id,\n        \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url, \"location\": self.location,\n        \"department\": self.department, \"employment_type\": self.employment_type,\n        \"posted_at\": self.posted_at, \"salary_range\": self.salary_range,\n        \"key\": self.key, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — `content_hash` / `key` recomputed multiple times per job — `store.py:67`, `models.py:55-69`\n\n`content_hash` and `key` are plain `@property` (recomputed on every access, `content_hash` does a SHA-256 hash each time). In `diff()`, for a \"changed\" job, `job.content_hash` is computed once for the comparison (line 67) and again inside `to_row()` (line 89) — 2x SHA-256 per changed job. `job.key` is accessed 2-3x per job across the loop. Minor compared to #1–#3, but free to fix while touching this code: compute once locally in the loop and reuse (`key = job.key; h = job.content_hash`) instead of re-deriving from properties.\n\nThe bigger caching win here is really #1 — the in-memory `existing` dict *is* the cache; right now `diff()` re-derives \"does this key exist\" from the DB per-row instead of caching the whole table's keys/hashes for the duration of the run.\n\n### 5. Memory leaks\n\nI didn't find classic leaks (unbounded caches, unclosed connections, growing globals). Resource lifecycle is handled correctly: `Store` is always used via `with Store(...) as store:` (both `pipeline.py:42` and `agent.py:73`/`126`), and `fetch_all()` closes its `httpx.AsyncClient` in a `finally` only when it created it (`fetchers.py:783-787`). The closest thing to a leak-shaped issue is #3 — holding full raw API payloads in memory for every `Job` across a 114-source run inflates peak RSS during a run, but it's released at process exit, not an actual leak.\n\n### Priority order\n1. `store.diff()` batch rewrite (#1) — biggest win, straightforward, low risk.\n2. Drop/streamline `Job.raw` (#3) — cheap, removes real deep-copy waste.\n3. Hoist regex compilation in `filters.py` (#2) — cheap, easy.\n4. Minor hash/key de-dup in `diff()` (#4) — do while you're already editing `diff()`.\n\nWant me to implement the `store.diff()` rewrite and the `filters.py` fix now?\n",
